{
  "doc_id": "40600",
  "text": "There are multiple considerations to our finding that transcriptional response in mouse models reflects human diseases so poorly, including the evolutional distance between mice and humans, the complexity of the human disease, the inbred nature of the mouse model, and often, the use of single mechanistic models [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In addition, differences in cellular composition between mouse and human tissues [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] can contribute to the differences seen in the molecular response. Additionally, the different temporal spans of recovery from disease between patients and mouse models are an inherent problem in the use of mouse models. Late events related to the clinical care of the patients (such as fluids, drugs, surgery, and life support) likely alter genomic responses that are not captured in murine models.",
